      <div xml:id="NA58-kiḷavi">
        <p type="edition">itu pakaṟkuṟi vantu nīṅkun talaimakaṉ pōkku nōkkit (EN, EV: nīkkit) tōḻi iraviṉmēl (EN, ER: māviṉmēl) vaittuc colliyatu.</p>
        <p type="translation" xml:lang="en">This is what the confidante said, putting it on the night, having seen HIM go who had come to the day tryst [and] left.</p>
      </div>
      <div xml:id="NA58">
        <lg type="edition">
<l>            peṟumutu celvar poṉṉuṭaip putalvar</l>
<l>            ciṟutōṭ kōtta cevvarip paṟaiyiṉ</l>
<l>            kaṇṇakat teḻutiya kurīip pōlak</l>
<l>            kōlkoṇ ṭalaikkap paṭīiyar mātō</l>
<l>            vīrai vēṇmāṉ veḷiyaṉ ṟittaṉ </l>
<l>            muracumutaṟ koḷīiya mālai viḷakkiṉ</l>
<l>            veṇkō ṭiyampa nuṇpaṉi yarumpak</l>
<l>            kaiyaṟa vanta poḻutoṭu meycōrn</l>
<l>            tavala neñciṉam peyara vuyartirai</l>
<l>            nīṭunīrp paṉittuṟaic cērppa </l>
<l>            ṉōṭutēr nuṇṇuka nuḻaitta māvē.</l>
            </lg>
       <lg type="translation" xml:lang="en">
<l>Shouldn't they be slapped<note place="foot"><term xml:lang="ta">paṭīiyar mātō</term>: what may be the impact of <term xml:lang="ta">mātō</term>? Can it be a rhetorical question, implying the uncomfortable truth that there is actually no means to bring HIM here any faster?</note> with a stick,</l>
<l rend="indent3">like the bird<note place="foot">The majority of the witnesses read <term xml:lang="ta">kurīi</term>, a small bird, which might or might not be a likely picture to adorn a child's drum, but how to imagine a bird-shaped stick for whipping horses? Preferable might be here, with G1+2, <term xml:lang="ta">kuṟiyē</term>, in spite of the problem of encountering an <term xml:lang="ta">-ē</term> in the middle of a subordinate period, but unfortunately this looks like an attempt at emendation.</note> drawn into the eye</l>
<l rend="indent3">of the red-lined drum stringed to the small shoulder</l>
<l rend="indent3">of the gold-adorned(?)<note place="foot"><term xml:lang="foot">poṉ-uṭai</term> can hardly mean anything else but that the child is wearing golden ornaments, as is attested elsewhere (cf. KT 148).</note> son of great old<note place="foot">Or: “wealthy people of old”.</note> wealthy people,</l>
<l>– the horses harnessed to the fine yoke of the running chariot</l>
<l>of the man from the coast of chilly ghats by the long water</l>
<l rend="indent">with high waves,</l>
<l rend="indent2">while we with an unhappy heart are agitated,</l>
<l rend="indent2">[our] body languishing with the time come to end [all] action,</l>
<l rend="indent3">while fine dew buds, while white conches sound,</l>
<l>when they announce evening by beating the bottom of the drum(?)<note place="foot">The message of this line seems clear enough, but syntax and semantics are not so. Why a conditional (<term xml:lang="ta">viḷakkiṉ</term>) instead of another infinitive, all the more since it can only be understood in a temporal way? And then <term xml:lang="ta">koḷiya</term>, an inf. that seems to have the function of a verbal noun (preferably one marked by <term xml:lang="ta">-iṉ</term>). As for its meaning, probably taking up the bottom of a drum may mean beginning to beat it.</note></l>
<l rend="indent3">of Veḷiyaṉ Tittaṉ, the son of Vīrai Vēṇ?</l>
    </lg>
